Data Summarization

  • Data summarization (as part of an exploratory analysis) is all about discovery: What is your data saying?
    • Describe data with numerical summaries (i.e., statistics).
    • Visualize data with graphical summaries.
  • How we summarize depends on whether the data is discrete or continuous.
    • Discrete is also called qualitative or categorical.
    • Continuous is also called quantitative or numerical.
  • We will use both dplyr and ggplot2 to summarize data.

library(tidyverse)

Describing Discrete Data

The simplest numeric summary for a discrete variable is a count.

mpg %>% 
  count(manufacturer)
## # A tibble: 15 x 2
##    manufacturer     n
##    <chr>        <int>
##  1 audi            18
##  2 chevrolet       19
##  3 dodge           37
##  4 ford            25
##  5 honda            9
##  6 hyundai         14
##  7 jeep             8
##  8 land rover       4
##  9 lincoln          3
## 10 mercury          4
## 11 nissan          13
## 12 pontiac          5
## 13 subaru          14
## 14 toyota          34
## 15 volkswagen      27

  • Now get a count by both manufacturer and drive type to produce a “tidy” cross-tab.
  • Save this as a new data frame car_count.

car_count <- mpg %>% 
  count(manufacturer, drv)

Visualizing Discrete Data

ggplot2 uses a consistent grammar of graphics built with layers.

  1. Data Data to visualize.
  2. Aesthetics Mapping graphical elements to data.
  3. Geometries Or “geom,” the graphic representing the data.

Plot our car_count data (note how + is different from %>%).

ggplot(car_count, aes(x = manufacturer, y = n)) +
  geom_col()

  • Lets visualize a second variable. Add the aesthetic fill = drv.
  • The geom position argument is set to "stack" by default. Try "dodge" and "fill" instead.

ggplot(car_count, aes(x = manufacturer, y = n, fill = drv)) +
  geom_col()

ggplot(car_count, aes(x = manufacturer, y = n, fill = drv)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")

ggplot(car_count, aes(x = manufacturer, y = n, fill = drv)) +
  geom_col(position = "fill")

Describing Continuous Data

The simplest numeric summary for a continuous variable is a mean.

mpg %>%
  summarize(avg_hwy = mean(hwy))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   avg_hwy
##     <dbl>
## 1    23.4

Note that summarize() is a more general version of count().

  • Compute the mean of both highway and city miles per gallon.
  • We can also compute the mode, median, variance, standard deviation, minimum, maximum, etc.

mpg %>% 
  summarize(avg_hwy = mean(hwy), avg_cty = mean(cty))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   avg_hwy avg_cty
##     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1    23.4    16.9

Visualizing Continuous Data

With discrete data, we had to create a summary before we created a plot (which is typical).

For continuous data, we can often plot without a summary. Lets plot the distribution of highway miles per gallon.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Visualize the relationship between highway and city MPG.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  geom_point()

  • What do we do if there is overplotting? Theres a geom for that.
  • Play with the size and alpha geom arguments.
  • Add a geom_smooth() layer.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = 0.5)

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Describing Discrete and Continuous Data

Grouped summaries provide a powerful solution for describing a combination of discrete and continuous data.

mpg %>%
  group_by(manufacturer) %>%
  summarize(
    n = n(),
    avg_hwy = mean(hwy),
    avg_cty = mean(cty)
  )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 15 x 4
##    manufacturer     n avg_hwy avg_cty
##    <chr>        <int>   <dbl>   <dbl>
##  1 audi            18    26.4    17.6
##  2 chevrolet       19    21.9    15  
##  3 dodge           37    17.9    13.1
##  4 ford            25    19.4    14  
##  5 honda            9    32.6    24.4
##  6 hyundai         14    26.9    18.6
##  7 jeep             8    17.6    13.5
##  8 land rover       4    16.5    11.5
##  9 lincoln          3    17      11.3
## 10 mercury          4    18      13.2
## 11 nissan          13    24.6    18.1
## 12 pontiac          5    26.4    17  
## 13 subaru          14    25.6    19.3
## 14 toyota          34    24.9    18.5
## 15 volkswagen      27    29.2    20.9

  • count() is a wrapper around a grouped summary with n().
  • Grouping by a discrete variable is equivalent to filtering the data separately for each value of the group variable.
  • Now group by manufacturer and fuel type and arrange the summary in descending order by average highway MPG.

mpg %>% 
  group_by(manufacturer, fl) %>% 
  summarize(
    n = n(), 
    avg_hwy = mean(hwy), 
    avg_cty = mean(cty)
  ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg_hwy))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'manufacturer' (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 32 x 5

##    manufacturer fl        n avg_hwy avg_cty

##  2 honda        c         1    36      24  
##  3 honda        r         6    33.2    25.3
##  4 honda        p         2    29      22  
##  5 volkswagen   p        11    28.1    19.6

Visualizing Discrete and Continuous Data

There are geoms specific to visualizing the relationship between discrete and continuous data.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = manufacturer, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot()

But there are a variety of other options to quickly create impressive visuals.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  • Add the aesthetic color = fl.
  • Add the layer facet_wrap(~ manufacturer).

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color = fl)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color = fl)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ manufacturer)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
